Diagnosis.
The genus is characterised and distinguishable from any other ophionine genera by the following combination of character states: mandible weakly to strongly tapered and more or less twisted (
Figs 2, 3
, 
6
); ocelli large, and sometimes adjacent or close to eyes (
Figs 2–4
); occipital carina usually complete; posterior transverse carina of mesosternum usually complete; discosubmarginal cell of fore wing with fenestra and often with sclerites (
Fig. 5
); ramellus of fore wing usually absent (
Fig. 5
); inner mesal surface of fore tibial spur without a membranous flange; and outer distal margin of mid and hind trochantelli simple, and usually without a decurved tooth.
